{{Infobox saint | name = Abiathar and Sidonia | image = | imagesize = | alt = | caption = | titles = Saints | birth_date = | birth_place = | death_date = | death_place = | venerated_in = Georgian Orthodox Church | beatified_date = | beatified_place = | beatified_by = | canonized_date = | canonized_place = | canonized_by = | major_shrine = | feast_day = October 1 | attributes = | patronage = | issues = | suppressed_date = | suppressed_by = | quote = }} '''Abiathar and Sidonia''' were a legendary [[Jewish]] priest of [[Mtskheta]] and his daughter. Abiathar is said to have been the first person [[Saint Nino]] converted to [[Christianity]]. An apocryphal account of the life and miracles of Saint Nino is attributed to them. They are regarded as [[saint]]s in the church in [[Georgia (country)|Georgia]], and are mentioned in Bessarion's ''[[The Saints of Georgia]]'' and the ''[[Menologium der Orthodox-Katholischen Kirche des Morgenlandes]]''.
It is said that after the death of Christ his Robe was carried to [[Mtskheta]] by Elioz, Sidonia's brother. After having listened to her brother's grief story about the death of Christ she "clutched the Robe to her breast and immediately gave up her spirit". She was buried with the Saint Robe in her embrace.<ref>[http://orthochristian.com/107099.html/ KING MIRIAN AND QUEEN NANA OF MTSKHETA, ST. ABIATHAR OF MTSKHETA, AND ST. SIDONIA, DISCIPLE OF ST. NINA] Retrieved on 18 Feb 2018</ref> And Abiathar and her daughter Sidonia are also considered to be the first Georgian writers. A lot of pseudo-epigraphical texts that tell about spreading of Christianity in Georgia are ascribed to them.
Their [[feast day]] is celebrated on October 1 in Georgia.
The name "[[Abiathar]]" is derived from a Biblical character, a priest of the Jerusalem Temple in the time of [[King David]].
