[[Commodore (Royal Navy)|Commodore]] '''Henry Douglas King''' [[Order of the Bath|CB]], [[Order of the British Empire|CBE]], [[Her Majesty's Most Honourable Privy Council|PC]], [[Distinguished Service Order|DSO]], [[Volunteer Decoration|VD]] (1 June 1877 – 20 August 1930), known as '''Douglas King''', was a British naval commander and [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] politician. He served under [[Stanley Baldwin]] as [[Financial Secretary to the War Office]] between 1924 and 1928 and as [[Secretary for Mines]] between 1928 and 1929.

==Early life==
King trained as a Merchant Navy officer in HMS Conway from 1891 to 1893. After Conway he served initially in the mercantile navy, then served in the [[Royal Navy]] before joining [[Peninsular and Oriental Steam Navigation Company|P & O]]. He left the sea in 1899 and took up farming for a short while. However, he soon turned to studying law and was [[Call to the Bar|called to the Bar]], [[Middle Temple]], in 1905. He stood as the Conservative candidate for [[North Norfolk (UK Parliament constituency)|Norfolk North]] in the two general elections of 1910, but was defeated on both occasions. At the outbreak of the [[First World War]] in 1914 he obtained a commission in the [[Royal Navy Volunteer Reserve]] and served at the [[Siege of Antwerp (1914)|Siege of Antwerp]] and [[Gallipoli Campaign|Gallipoli]].<ref name="eveningpost">[http://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/cgi-bin/paperspast?a=d&d=EP19290706.2.175 ''Evening Post'', 6 July 1929]</ref> He was awarded the [[Distinguished Service Order]] in recognition of his services at Gallipoli in 1915.<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=29358 |date=5 November 1915 |page=11929 }}</ref> He was also given the French [[Croix de Guerre]]<ref name="eveningpost"/> and was appointed a Commander of the [[Order of the British Empire]] in 1919.<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=31118 |date=10 January 1919 |page=512 }}</ref>

==Political career==
At the 1918 general election King once again stood for [[North Norfolk (UK Parliament constituency)|Norfolk North]] and was this time elected.<ref>{{Rayment-hc|n|2|date=March 2012}}</ref> In parliament he initially served as [[Parliamentary Private Secretary]] to [[Leslie Orme Wilson|Sir Leslie Wilson]], Chairman of the National Maritime Board, and then to [[Hamar Greenwood, 1st Viscount Greenwood|Sir Hamar Greenwood]], the [[Chief Secretary for Ireland]]. In 1921 he was appointed a Conservative [[whip (politics)|whip]]. The following year he was returned to parliament for [[Paddington South (UK Parliament constituency)|Paddington South]]<ref>{{Rayment-hc|p|1|date=March 2012}}</ref> and entered the government under [[Bonar Law]] as a [[Lord of the Treasury]] (government whip),<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=32776 |date=12 December 1922 |page=8793 }}</ref> a position he held until January 1924, the last year under the premiership of [[Stanley Baldwin]]. When the Conservatives returned to office in November 1924, King was made [[Financial Secretary to the War Office]] and a member of the Army Council.<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=33001 |date=12 December 1924 |page=9057 }}</ref> He held this post until 1928, and was then [[Secretary for Mines]] until the Baldwin administration fell in 1929. The latter year he was also sworn of the [[Her Majesty's Most Honourable Privy Council|Privy Council]] following the [[1929 Dissolution Honours]].<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=33512 |date=29 June 1929 |page=4354 }}</ref> He had previously been made a Companion of the [[Order of the Bath]] in 1927.<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=33280 |date=31 May 1927 |page=3605 }}</ref>

==Personal life==
King married the only daughter of W. R. Swan, of [[Adelaide]], [[Australia]].<ref name="eveningpost"/> On 20 August 1930 King's cutter yacht ''Islander'' sank in a gale off [[Fowey]], [[Cornwall]]. All six aboard, including King himself, were lost. His memorial is at All Saints Church, Upper Sheringham, Norfolk. The memorial states that the yacht Islander was 'smashed to pieces' on the rocky coast of Lantivet Bay, Cornwall during a 'fierce summer storm'.
It goes on: "At sunset in the calm stillness of a beautiful summer evening, his ashes were, by his own wish, taken out to sea by the Sheringham lifeboat and within sight of his old home scattered over the face of the waters".

