The '''McRoberts maneuver''' is an [[obstetrical]] maneuver used to assist in [[childbirth]]. It is named after William A. McRoberts, Jr.<ref>{{Cite journal | last1 = Gonik | first1 = B. | last2 = Stringer | first2 = C. A. | last3 = Held | first3 = B. | title = An alternate maneuver for management of shoulder dystocia | journal = American Journal of Obstetrics and Gynecology | volume = 145 | issue = 7 | pages = 882–884 | year = 1983 | pmid = 6837666 | doi = 10.1016/0002-9378(83)90694-4 }}</ref> It is employed in case of [[shoulder dystocia]] during [[childbirth]] and involves hyperflexing the mother's legs tightly to her abdomen. It is effective due to the increased mobility at the sacroiliac joint during pregnancy, allowing rotation of the pelvis and facilitating the release of the fetal shoulder.<ref>{{Cite journal | last1 = Gherman | first1 = R. B. | last2 = Tramont | first2 = J. | last3 = Muffley | first3 = P. | last4 = Goodwin | first4 = T. M. | title = Analysis of McRoberts' maneuver by x-ray pelvimetry | journal = Obstetrics and gynecology | volume = 95 | issue = 1 | pages = 43–47 | year = 2000 | pmid = 10636500 | doi=10.1016/s0029-7844(99)00445-7}}</ref> If this maneuver does not succeed, an assistant applies pressure on the lower abdomen (suprapubic pressure), and the delivered head is also gently pulled. The technique is effective in about 42% of cases.<ref>{{cite book |last= Kish|first= Karen|author2=Joseph V. Collea|editor= Alan H. DeCherney|others= Lauren Nathan|title= Current Obstetric & Gynecologic Diagnosis & Treatment|edition= Ninth|year= 2003|publisher= Lange/McGraw-Hill|isbn= 0-07-118207-1|pages= 381–382|chapter= Malpresentation & Cord Prolaps (Chapter 21)}}</ref>
== See also == * [[Woods' screw maneuver]] * [[Zavanelli maneuver]] * [[Shoulder dystocia]] * [[Shoulder dystocia#Treatment|Treatment of shoulder dystocia]] * [[Childbirth#The mechanics of birth|The mechanics of birth]]
