{{ Infobox Person | name = Mehmet Altınsoy | birth_date = 1924 | birth_place = Aksaray | death_date = 17 February 2007 | death_place = Ankara | nationality = Turkish | occupation = Politician }}
'''Mehmet Altınsoy''' (1924 in [[Aksaray]] – 17 February 2007 in [[Ankara]]) was a [[Turkish people|Turkish]] politician, co-founder of the [[Motherland Party (Turkey)|Motherland Party]] ({{lang-tr|Anavatan Partisi}}), [[List of mayors of Ankara|Mayor of Ankara]] and minister of state.<ref>Biyografi.net - [http://www.biyografi.net/kisiayrinti.asp?kisiid=279 ''Biography of Mehmet Altınsoy''] {{tr icon}}</ref>
==Biography== Mehmet Altınsoy became a lawyer after graduating from the [[Ankara University, Law School|Law School at Ankara University]]. He entered politics after the [[1960 Turkish coup d'état|military coup of 1960]]. By keeping his nationalist-conservative line in the last 50 years of the history of Turkish politics, he was a member of several political parties like [[Nationalist Movement Party]], [[Motherland Party (Turkey)|Motherland Party]] and finally [[Welfare Party]].
He was appointed a founding member of the [[Turkish Grand National Assembly|parliament]] in 1961. He was appointed minister in the cabinet of [[List of Prime Ministers of Turkey|Prime Minister]] [[Suat Hayri Ürgüplü]] in 1965. Mehmet Altınsoy served until 1969 in the parliament. In 1983, he was among the founders of [[Turgut Özal]]'s Motherland Party. Between 1984 and 1989, he served as the mayor of Greater Ankara and realized major [[infrastructure]] projects with the support of Prime Minister Turgut Özal, whom Altınsoy was considered to be a confidant. He became a minister for the second time, in the Welfare Party and [[True Path Party]] coalition cabinet in 1996-1997.
After lying three days in a [[coma]] at the [[Atatürk Hospital]] in [[Ankara]], where he was brought in following an [[intracranial hemorrhage]] caused by [[hypertension]], he died on 17 February 2007. Mehmet Altınsoy was first married with Necla (1928-2001), the daughter of former [[Diyanet İşleri Başkanlığı|President of Religious Affairs]] Ahmet Hamdi Akseki, with whom he had two daughters Yasemin and Sedef. He was buried at [[Karşıyaka Cemetery]] after the funeral service in [[Kocatepe Mosque]].<ref>Haberler.com - [http://www.haberler.com/eski-bakanlardan-mehmet-altinsoy-un-cenazesi-haberi/ ''News - Funeral of Mehmet Altınsoy''] {{tr icon}}</ref>
{{s-start}} {{s-off}} {{succession box | before=[[Süleyman Önder]] | title=[[List of mayors of Ankara|Mayor of Ankara]] | years=1984&ndash;1989 | after=[[Murat Karayalçın]] }} {{s-end}}
